commentBody:
@DebAmlen

BOO BIRDS treasonously boo at their *home* team, feeling, no doubt, a sense of WASTED POTENTIAL.

I guess I just ATTED Ms Amlen.  Until today I would have thought I @-ed her.

@Steve L 

If the Philly BOOBIRDs boo the home team, then who boos Santa Clause?




Oh, I remember, it's the emus.

@Steve L 
Hand up for (almost always!) skipping the column.  I don't need hints--I only come here after I finish the puzzle--or, rarely, give up.  The few times I read it, the 'Tricky Clues' ...weren't.  It added nothing to my enjoyment and met no needs.
I like the Comments (and usually look for particular 'regulars' if I have time) but I don't always have the time after breakfast. ( I'm up early, but go out walking first, then print and solve the puzzle wiith coffee, and so I'm never one of the EarlyBirds.)

@Mike 
When either of us gets going, it's either you Orion a roll.

The emus probably liked your Vega tempt, though.

@Mike 

My stars!

You can't trust Vegans.  They're too lyrical.

@Francis 

*sigh* edit:  "...serious with me THAN mad at me."

hate when that happens.

@Bonnie Ann 

I'm right there with you.  I only know things like "jelloshots" from working with younger (sometimes *much* younger) people, and listening to them talk about their exploits.

Now that I'm retired, I'm sure new things will creep in.  I didn't know EDGELORD, at all, and it was purely by making real words for the compound word that got me by.  I'd also never heard of SINBIN, but it made sense that a hockey player was put there for the "sin" of (probably) bashing another player's head with his stick.

@Bonnie Ann 
Apparently BOOBIRD has been around longer than I have— and I’m well into my eighth decade! I only recall having heard it in the last few years, though. I am also not a football or hockey fan, but was able to complete this in below average time, with the help of the crosses, despite a couple unfamiliar terms. ( I like the inclusion of contemporary usage in the puzzle, as it often occasions a TIL moment… and may keep me from feeling like too much of a dinosaur should I need to converse with a young ‘un.)

Perhaps my biggest problem was the very familiar “aloe”, which as Deb noted, went in almost automatically, before BALM became obvious.

@Bonnie Ann 

Your clearsighted and cheerful acceptance of the of the inevitable turning of time and tide, without blame or bluster, made my day!

Wisdom. Appreciated. Thank you.

@Francis 

Hi Francis.  I was patting myself on the back for knowing "troll" and I tried to force webtroll in all sorts of incorrect imaginative ways.  When I finally checked Deb's hints and saw EDGELORD (of course that whole corner of the puzzle fell into place nicely). So, here's the thing, when you live long enough (what a wonderful thing, right?), you have the opportunity to learn more than one generation of newly created words to describe all the new things that pop up.  Congratulations on being included in the Jelloshots conversations. That must have been fun.
Cheers.

@Darcey O’D 

I had ALOE first, too. It seems to be ubiquitous in puzzles.  All those juicy vowels! I'm entering my eighties next year.  I can't wait for more TIL moments.  Such fun to learn BOOBIRDS isn't new, just new to this old yardbird.

Cheers.

@Teresa 

I feel so much younger than my almost eighty years.  I have so enjoyed my seventies! What a blast!  Puzzles keep me young. TIL moments are the best elixir for aging. I never heard of a SECRETMENU either.  If it's good, why keep it a secret?
Cheers.

@Hope 

Thank you, Hope.  You made my day. 

Cheers.

@rajeevfromca 

I did because there were so many answers I did not know and yet my time was 15% less than average.

Edgelord, glum, and broom slowed me down until I got APLUS.

@pmom 

I did think of CAT WOMAN , but the BOO was already in place, so I was redirected.
I had no clue about either, really.

@Barry Ancona 

In fact, this is the third time in 2024 that BOOBIRDS has been an entry.  I guess the puzzle is easier for those who remember previous iterations of the entries.


!!!!

@Mark 

Well, sorry about your streak, glad you are otherwise ok,
and rest assured I'll never compete with your streak.

@Joe 

Today I learned “adit”.

The emus probably already knew it.

@Mean Old Lady 

Maybe one day ANOLE, which I see with some frequency here in North Carolina.  Emus not so much.

AFFINE is another I think undeservedly overlooked.

@Jim 
Same in Band in HS...

I don't know what they did when Bob graduated; (I was a yr ahead of him.)

@Times Rita 

A “bomb” is a football term for a long pass, so the receiver GOES DEEP to prepare to receive the pass. 

PS: I did not know this either, so while I got the answer from crosses, it did not feel satisfying.

@Jim 
_ATWOMAN could only "B" or "C", since, as a character, Ratwoman never caught on. Older comic geeks might remember Fatwoman, but since the advent of size-shaming and low-cholesterol diets, she has been rightly dropped from the canon.

The Queer comic *The Mostly Unfabulous Life of Ethan Green*, by Eric Orner, featured the Hat Sisters, a pair of crime-fighting super-hero(ine) drag queens.

@Bill 

And as most people know, Catwoman was not a superhero, but rather a villain. 

Julie Newmar, Eartha Kitt, etc.

@Bill 

I haven’t thought of Ethan Green in years. There used to be a weekly LGBTQ news magazine in Dallas, Houston, Austin and probably a few other Texas cities. I think Ethan Green was a serialized strip in that magazine. 

Thanks!

@Steve L 

Doh!  Of course!  (Is my face red?)  Catwoman was not a superhero, so batwoman the unambiguous answer.

Since no one asked, Kane is the last name of the person attributed as the creator of Batman, though some argue that attribution.

@John Peil 
Next time you'll remember that MEAD is not beer.

It's amazing, though, how many alcoholic beverages are attributed to inventive monks...

@Bill 
(This was meant to be in response to @ John Peil, rwo posts below).






Hair of the emu.

@Bill 

Years ago, our favorite local Mexican joint went upscale, redecorating both the restaurant and the menu - and took _pollo verde_ off the list. Like your saag paneer, we were able to continue to ask for it with successful results... until we couldn't, and resorted to pollo asada instead. 

I was shocked then and continue to be amazed now, that very popular staples such as saag paneer and pollo verde would be removed from a menu. Especially if they're actually still making the saag, just not advertising it! Luckily for you.  :)

@Xword Junkie Although @Eric is correct about the cluing mechanics, your instincts about the weirdness of connecting 'pho' and 'soup' are spot on. Pho is _noodles_. Not soup. 

In VNese, 'soup' is either 'canh' (light broth usually served with office lunch) or 'súp' (soupier soupy soups; loanword from French).

Yes I know we play by 'common-usage English' rules here. But who can pass up the opportunity to be pedantically correct? :-)

@Grant 
Interesting. I honestly thought your Jell-o was the same as our jelly. 
Jelly Babies are delicious, a childhood staple, though these days I find them too sweet. My favourites were always the black ones. Quite licorishey.

@Nobis Miserere 

I’ve never had one, and though I first heard the term years ago, I only recently learned that the Jell-O is not in liquid form. 

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jello_shot" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jello_shot</a>

@Barry Ancona 

I did not. I couldn’t imagine downing an ounce or so of solidified Jell-O (once of my least favorite foods). 

I also assumed that Jell-O shots had become popular after my college years in the late 1970s and early 1980s. I was surprised to learn (also relatively recently) that they go back to the 1950s.

@CaptainQuahog 

It’s so tough, they are family members. For over 30 thousand years, we have bred them to care for us, maybe more than we deserve.

Condolences. I’ve been there, hate it, but love them.

@Josh 

I assume this was directed at Cap'n Quahog.

me, too, I have all the sympathy in the world for someone who's lost  a beloved companion pet.

@Justin 

No Means No! Thank you - I certainly did get my 80's PSA slogans mixed up. 

Empowerment and self-determination through the word No. If only life were that simple... 


@Amy

Thank you for putting it so much more clearly than I did. Unambiguous and explicit consent is important. The movement seemed to reach my college the year I was overseas, and when oh-so- worldly me returned to upstate New York, I thought I didn't need such baldface language...

@Francis 

Someone's got to get the trend started!

You have my full support!

@Francis 

So far my main response to you has not been posted It's been about 30 minutes 


!

@AABB 

And my first response must have been racier still as I see it still hasn't shown up! 

Those prudish emus!!

@SteveG_VA 

I'm no expert, but I don't think that kind of progress is at all linear.  It's slow, slow, slow, and then suddenly it changes.

At least we can hope for that.

@Min 

It almost feels like a sociological experiment.  A community of people most of whom have no other contact.  Totally faceless, totally contextless, except for what context is shared in the posts.

Moreover, it's strange to think that if something happened to one of the regular posters here, it's possible, and even likely, they'd disappear without a hint of an explanation.
